overriding-and-specialization-sketch0.bodyMarkdown:
In object-oriented programming, method overriding allows a subclass to provide a specific implementation of a method that is already defined in its superclass. This is useful when the subclass needs to modify or extend the behavior of the method to suit its own needs.

For example, consider a base class `Animal` with a method `speak()`. A subclass `Dog` might override this method to provide a specific implementation:

```python
class Animal:
    def speak(self):
        return "Some sound"

class Dog(Animal):
    def speak(self):
        return "Woof!"
```

In this example, calling `speak()` on an instance of `Dog` will return "Woof!", while calling it on an instance of `Animal` will return "Some sound". This demonstrates how overriding allows subclasses to specialize behavior.

